Greetings from Los Angeles, and welcome back to In the Room. In tonight=E2=
=80=99s email, more news and notes on the turbulence at the Washington Post=
, where a week=E2=80=99s worth of restructuring, strategically placed leaks=
, and finger-pointing seems to be driving Jeff Bezos=E2=80=99s beleaguered =
paper toward yet another nadir. Is a late-Friday plea from Will Lewis enoug=
h to fix it?

But first, a couple CNN scoops=E2=80=A6

=F0=9F=93=BA A primetime change: CNN C.E.O. Mark Thompson has elevated Ande=
rson Cooper=E2=80=99s longtime executive producer Charlie Moore to vice pre=
sident of news, overseeing the 7 p.m. to midnight hours. Moore is one of th=
e most highly respected E.P.s at the company, and his move to primetime may=
 portend further changes to the news network=E2=80=99s struggling nighttime=
 lineup. To her credit,
Kaitlan Collins has been playing to her strengths recently with some very w=
ell-conducted interviews (Bill Barr, etcetera) that actually make for good =
television, but the ratings indicate the broader primetime strategy is long=
 overdue for an overhaul.

=F0=9F=92=BB An A.P. deal: CNN has struck a deal with the Associated Press =
to use their copy for digital stories, the first time it has done so since =
cutting ties with the wire service in 2010. The deal would appear to porten=
d further staff cuts, and that=E2=80=99s certainly how some CNN insiders ar=
e reading it. A spokesperson tells me it=E2=80=99s simply intended to free =
up reporters to spend more time on original, longform, and investigative re=
porting. =E2=80=9CThis allows our writers to spend more time on enterprise =
reporting and less time on quick writes,=E2=80=9D the spokesperson said. =
=E2=80=9CThe goal is to enhance our editorial reach while allowing us to fo=
cus on key editorial priorities.=E2=80=9D

