          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">To be fair, it was =
inarguably a demotion. Even if Bezos and Lewis had envisioned this <i>third=
 newsroom</i> as a vehicle to return the <i>Post </i>to profitability, Buzb=
ee was already in charge of all that content=E2=80=94in addition to everyth=
ing else. Her decision to entertain the diminished role, in the first place=
, is one of the more bizarre elements of this saga. Either Lewis and Bezos =
were preternaturally compelling or Buzbee was naive, perhaps both.<br/><br/=
>Understandably, Buzbee probably chafed at the way Lewis had handled the wh=
ole transition, initially suggesting she might even have some consideration=
 over her replacement=E2=80=94a truly unfathomable suggestion, on its face,=
 but one that also appeared duplicitous given that he had already picked Wi=
nnett for the job. Anyway, two weeks ago, she asked to keep her current job=
, and Lewis instead recruited
Murray to step in until Winnett=E2=80=99s arrival later this year, at which=
 point Murray will take over that <i>third newsroom</i>. Lewis sent out his=
 initial and hasty and jarring email announcing the news on Sunday night. <=
br/><br/>But Buzbee, it turned out, appeared to have developed her own attu=
ned survival instincts from a lifetime in sharp-elbowed newsrooms. Before l=
eaving the <i>Post</i>, Buzbee told colleagues and associates both inside a=
nd outside the building that Lewis had <i>twice</i>, once in March and agai=
n in May, tried to pressure her to forgo running stories that related to hi=
s association with the decade-old Murdoch phone-hacking scandal. In brief: =
Murdoch had appointed Lewis to oversee a committee responsible for handling=
 his publishing giant=E2=80=99s response to the phone-hacking scandal, and =
an ongoing lawsuit alleges that Lewis was involved with an effort to concea=
l evidence from authorities. Lewis has maintained his innocence, and was pr=
esumably cleared by
Sucherman=E2=80=99s due diligence during his recruitment (either way, it=E2=
=80=99s not as though Bezos didn=E2=80=99t know about this). In both instan=
ces, the <i>Post </i>ran the stories, and Lewis later told the <i>Post </i>=
that he =E2=80=9Cdid not pressure [Buzbee] in any way.=E2=80=9D Also, for w=
hat it=E2=80=99s worth, these episodes didn=E2=80=99t seem to bother Buzbee=
 all that much <i>before</i> she became hip to the plan to manage her aside=
=2E<br/><br/>Nevertheless, in the wa=
ke of Buzbee=E2=80=99s ouster, her versio=
n of these exchanges found its way to <i>The New York Times</i>, where they=
 quickly became a story in their own right and reframed the narrative aroun=
d Buzbee=E2=80=99s defenestration. A decade ago, <b>Jill Abramson </b>manif=
ested her version of her ouster into <b>Ken Auletta</b>=E2=80=99s charitabl=
e copy at <i>The New Yorker.</i> Now, Buzbee was able to refocus a narrativ=
e about mismanagement=E2=80=94before Sunday, she didn=E2=80=99t have <i>tha=
t</i> many fans in her underwater newsroom=E2=80=94into journalistic martyr=
dom, all the
while portraying Lewis as an unethical Murdoch interloper looking to cleans=
e his reputation and interfere with his newsroom. The <i>Times </i>stipulat=
ed that these interactions =E2=80=9Cwere not the primary reason for her res=
ignation,=E2=80=9D but it didn=E2=80=99t matter. Buzbee=E2=80=99s narrative=
 nailed Lewis where it hurt the most. Days after he told the newsroom that =
people <i>weren=E2=80=99t reading their stuff</i>, this account questioned =
his journalistic credibility. The Brit had been totally out-Washington-ed.<=
br/><br/>NPR media reporter <b>David Folkenflik </b>added fuel to the fire =
by dusting off his own, months-old anecdote about Lewis=E2=80=99s attempt t=
o offer him an exclusive interview in exchange for him not writing a phone-=
hacking story. Lewis would tell his own paper that his conversation with Fo=
lkenflik was off the record, while Folkenflik maintained that that agreemen=
t only pertained to the substance of the hacking case, not Lewis=E2=80=99s =
=E2=80=9Cefforts to induce me to kill my story.=E2=80=9D In any
event, the <i>Times </i>then decided to publish <i>yet another </i>story ab=
out Folkenflik=E2=80=99s own accusation against Lewis.<br/><br/><i>Finally,=
 </i>on Thursday night, the <i>Post </i>published its own meticulously re-r=
eported and characteristically unpunctual account of the whole affair. And =
that might reasonably have put a button on the matter if it weren=E2=80=99t=
 for the fact that Lewis himself went on the record with a number of respon=
ses that betrayed his Fleet Street sensibilities, manifested his own frustr=
ations, and only further estranged him from his growing body of sensitive i=
nternal critics, who have relatively conservative notions about the decorum=
 of their leaders. Lewis called Folkenflik =E2=80=9Can activist, not a jour=
nalist,=E2=80=9D and more or less came off sounding like a pissed-off jerk,=
 who was unmoved by his staffers=E2=80=99 concerns over the leadership tran=
sition <i>and </i>the phone-hacking issue. <br/><br/>In British parlance, i=
t was unequivocally an own goal. In the last
24 hours, <i>Post </i>rivals have declared that Lewis =E2=80=9Cis quickly l=
osing the confidence of his newsroom=E2=80=9D (CNN), and that =E2=80=9CLewi=
s=E2=80=99s loss of credibility may be difficult to overcome=E2=80=9D (Poli=
tico). And perhaps that=E2=80=99s why Stonesifer popped by the office on K =
Street today.<br/></td>
