          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The truth is a litt=
le more nuanced, of course. There are certainly many <i>Post </i>staffers w=
ho appear to be irate over the reports about Lewis=E2=80=99s exchanges with=
 Buzbee and Folkenflik. From my reporting, there seem to be far <i>more</i>=
 who are simply preoccupied by their anxiety over his new three-pronged new=
sroom strategy, and whether it will actually help their business. And there=
 are others who are actually <i>happy</i> to have Murray in charge of the n=
ewsroom, and seem somewhat bemused by the fact that Buzbee, who until now w=
as widely seen as an ineffective and uninspiring leader, has somehow sudden=
ly transformed into a saint. <br/><br/>In any case, merely half a year into=
 Lewis=E2=80=99s tenure, the <i>Post </i>once again finds itself in an utte=
rly awful situation. The business is still a disaster, and the man who oste=
nsibly has a plan to save the
newsroom from its malaise has instead become their latest scapegoat (first =
Fred, then Sally, now Will), limiting his efficacy to enforce his vision. T=
hese critics smell blood in the water, and may very well decide to make lif=
e even <i>harder</i> for him. Meanwhile, his boss, Bezos, hardly seems incl=
ined to fire the guy he just hired to enact this grand transformation and r=
everse it into a profitable enterprise. So Lewis will remain, but perhaps w=
ithout the buy-in that might have been necessary to enact his plan. <br/><b=
r/>And that may indeed be the biggest reveal of all here: However dire the =
<i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s commercial and editorial challenges, they pale in com=
parison to its cultural issues=E2=80=94and it=E2=80=99s not clear if those =
can be fixed. On Friday night, Lewis took a stab at repairing relations wit=
h a lengthy memo to staff in which he acknowledged, =E2=80=9CI need to impr=
ove how well I listen and how well I communicate so that we all agree more =
clearly where urgent improvements are
needed and why.=E2=80=9D He also announced that he would further address st=
affers=E2=80=99 questions about the =E2=80=9CThird Newsroom=E2=80=9D=E2=80=
=94evidently a proper noun, per the memo=E2=80=94and shared an official sta=
tement from the <i>Post </i>declaring that the <i>Times</i>=E2=80=99 covera=
ge of his interactions with Buzbee were =E2=80=9Cinaccurate.=E2=80=9D Lewis=
 =E2=80=9Cdid not pressure Ms. Buzbee from publishing any stories during he=
r tenure at The Post, including the stories she brought up to him,=E2=80=9D=
 it read. =E2=80=9CTo suggest otherwise is completely false.=E2=80=9D  <br/=
><br/>Lewis also made an appeal. =E2=80=9CHere is what I ask of you,=E2=80=
=9D he wrote, trying to end the longest week of his professional life on a =
high note. =E2=80=9CI know trust has been lost because of scars from the pa=
st and the back-and-forth from this week. Let=E2=80=99s leave those behind =
and start presuming the best of intent. If we do that, you will see where w=
e are going in a different light. We don=E2=80=99t have to agree about ever=
ything but we all are dedicated to building the
future of <i>The Post</i>, and mapping our way there together.=E2=80=9D<br/=
><br/>We=E2=80=99ll see if the memo gets the job done. One revelation from =
this week=E2=80=99s saga is the culture clash between Lewis=E2=80=99s unapo=
logetically blunt Fleet Street style=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cpeople are <i>not rea=
ding your stuff</i>,=E2=80=9D Folkenflik =E2=80=9Cis an activist=E2=80=9D=
=E2=80=94and the self-serious decorum of Washington journalists who see the=
